          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>The sternal angle (Angle of Louis) marks all of the following EXCEPT one. Which </p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The sternal angle (Angle of Louis) marks all of the following EXCEPT one. Which structure does it NOT correspond to?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>The level of the second costal cartilage</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The sternal angle does mark the 2nd costal cartilage — this is why it is the starting point for counting ribs anteriorly.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The bifurcation of the trachea into main bronchi</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct anatomy — the trachea bifurcates at the level of the sternal angle (T4/T5 disc posteriorly).</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The level of the jugular notch</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The jugular notch lies higher, at the upper border of the manubrium (around T2). The sternal angle is about 5 cm below it, where manubrium meets body.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The boundary between superior and inferior mediastinum</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct — the transverse plane through the sternal angle and T4/T5 disc separates the superior from the inferior mediastinum.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Revisit the sternal angle. It marks the 2nd costal cartilage, tracheal bifurcation, aortic arch limits, T4/T5 disc, and the superior/inferior mediastinum boundary — but NOT the jugular notch, which sits higher."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The sternal angle is the single most useful surface landmark in thoracic anatomy — but the jugular notch is a separate, higher landmark."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
